IT Budget




Citigroup, Inc. a multibank holding company, provides various financial services to customers in the United States and internationally. Citigroup is organized into three major business groups: Global Consumer, Corporate and Investment Banking, and Global Wealth Management. These divisions, along with… MoreCitigroup, Inc. a multibank holding company, provides various financial services to customers in the United States and internationally. Citigroup is organized into three major business groups: Global Consumer, Corporate and Investment Banking, and Global Wealth Management. These divisions, along with an additional group, Citigroup Alternative Investments, are considered stand alone business units. Other business units include the Regional Consumer Group, Citibank, Citi Cards, Citi Retail Services, Citi Commercial Bank, Citi Mortgage, Citi Institutional Client Corp., Citi Markets, Citi Research, Citi Private Bank, Citi Transaction Services and Citi Corporate and Investment Banking. Citigroup was formed in 1998 via merger of Citicorp and Travelers Group/Salomon Smith Barney.

Citigroup UK , Poland, Hungary, Spain, Ireland and Netherlands, as well as Citibank Brazil, China, Malaysia, Singapore, Indonesia, El Salvador, and Citibank Schweiz AG are profiled separately in RainKing, as are Citi Trends, Citigroup Global Markets Deutschland AG, Citi Habitats, CitiFinancial, and Citigroup Securities Indonesia.

Citigroup sold its OneMain Financial subsidiary to Springleaf in November, 2015.
• The organization expects its unstructured storage to grow more than 100% in the next 12 months.
• The organization's total data storage volume under management is more than 5 Petabytes.
• The organization's weekly backup is greater than 100TB. • Citigroup… More• The organization expects its unstructured storage to grow more than 100% in the next 12 months.
• The organization's total data storage volume under management is more than 5 Petabytes.
• The organization's weekly backup is greater than 100TB. • Citigroup Inc. maintains a $5-$10M data center operations contract.
• Citigroup Inc. maintains a $5-$10M legacy application support contract.
• Citigroup Inc. maintains a mobile application development contract.
• Citigroup Inc. maintains a more than $10M help desk management contract with IBM.
• Citigroup Inc. maintains a more than $10M help desk management contract.
• Citigroup Inc. maintains an infrastructure management contract.

IT Structure
• Citigroup Inc. created Citi FinTech in late 2015, as a technology development business unit.  The group is expected to release a mobile banking product in Q4 2016.
• Citigroup Inc. is currently implementing a voice biometrics application in the Asia Pacific region, to be rolled out across the company's other regions if the program is deemed a success.
• Automation has been a long-term focus for the company, and is expected to remain so for the next few years.  Reducing banking branch staff is a major goal of the program.


Citigroup Inc. runs its Information Technology efforts across North America with various business units, administration offices, data centers, and contact centers distributed across the US. Currently, the bulk of the IT staff is located within the New York and New Jersey regions with the company headquarters in New York, NY. The Chief Administrative Officer is responsible for business operations and IT under the entire umbrella of the Citi companies and business units. Since the recent re-organization of the company, the CAO is assisted by the IT Strategy Chief and Head of Operations and Technology in making executive decisions. 

Citigroup's IT department is organized into multiple major business divisions:

The Institutional Clients Group (ICG) oversees the Markets and Banking division as well as Citi Alternative Investments globally. This group boasts some of the largest spending and resource allocation within the enterprise, due to the Product Side Development of financial systems as well as market forecasting and stability technologies. Major areas of interest include Product and Technology Security, the Project Management Office, and regional development of systems and applications for Divisional Infrastructure operations.

The Global Consumer Group (GCG) oversees a variety of IT-influential segments, including client lending technology and consumer IT. The GCG Chief Information Officer is responsible for all internal IT Strategy and roadmaps such as Core Security Services, Vendor Management, and the GCG Internet and Mobile presence. The GCG Chief Technology Officer oversees the engineering functions. Within the GCG also resides CitiCards, the affiliate that controls Credit Technology and consumer lending. This group is currently investing heavily in deploying Hadoop-based solutions, data marketplace, self-service dashboard solutions. Its data volume is approximately 5 pb and is growing at an annual rate of 6-10%. Its data environment is somewhat integrated (25-50% of data on a single database architecture) and consists of data that is primarily deployed on premises in a purpose-built appliance. It uses a relational database to store data primarily sourced from enterprise applications and other machine-generated data (web logs, sensor logs, systems logs etc).

The company's Retail Services Group is hoping to deploy Retail Partner Initiatives in the near future.  It is currently investing heavily in hardware, interface, and storage solutions. Its data volume is approximately 5 pb and is growing at an annual rate of 11-20%. Its data environment is significantly integrated (50-75% of data on a single database architecture) and consists of data that is primarily deployed in a private cloud. The company uses a relational database to store data primarily sourced from enterprise applications. 

While those business units run their IT operations as standalone businesses, the Citi Operations and Technology Group handles the corporate enterprise IT department, which utilizes shared services models to distribute and control systems and services within the business units and corporate entities. The largest segment of the O&T unit is the Citigroup Architecture Technology Engineering (CATE) division, which maintains all Engineering Development, Messaging and Mobility, and all Solutions Development initiatives. The other large segment of O&T is the Enterprise Infrastructure division, which controls Data Center Management, Networks, Mainframes, and End-User Support.It uses NoSQL database (e.g. MongoDB) to store data primarily sourced from enterprise applications, other machine-generated data (web logs, sensor logs, systems logs etc.), and human-generated data/text (such as social media).

The main Infrastructure Platform at Citigroup is comprised of 14 data centers with approximately 60,000 virtual and physical servers. At its headquarters in New York, Citigroup Inc. uses disk backup across VTL, NAS, SAN, and DAS environment to back up its hybrid of block and file data. It uses netbackup as its main backup application. Its daily and weekly total data backup is 30TB and 60TB respectively, with a 2 hour backup window. Its backup growth is around 10+. Relating to its remote locations, data is backed up locally, and some remote locations have WAN optimization deployed. At its Atlanta, GA location, Citigroup Inc. uses disks to back up its hybrid of block and file data. It has a 7-8 hour backup window. 

To help improve and standardize security awareness between and within business units, a separate IT Security division has been set-up to monitor and control the security of information and technologies. Always a big spend division, this group handles extensive IT staff involved with IT Risk Management and Identity Management, which inform and teach security personnel within the business units how to spread security knowledge to all contacts within the company. Citigroup is planning to evaluate threat/intrusion detection technologies, security information and event management, (SIEM), malware protection technologies,and next generation firewall solutions in the next 6-12 months.  Additionally, it plans to increase security spending in digital rights management encryption, policy compliance and enforcement. Citigroup Inc. is planning to evaluate threat/intrusion detection technologies, SIEM (Security Information and Event Management, malware protection/technologies, and next-generation firewall technologies in the next 6-12 months. 

It uses a proprietary storage security solution and an in-house solution for its fraud detection. Citigroup Inc. has the following security safeguards in place:  regular policy reviews, documented incident response process, encryption of mobile devices, and malware and virus protection software on all devices. The company uses an MSSP to monitor treats across its networks, security devices and data. It currently runs non-critical applications, business applications, and storage/backup in a cloud environment.

The company uses McAfee for fraud protection and relating to security safeguards, the company has regular policy reviews, documented incident response processes, inventory of third parties, encryption of mobile devices, malware and virus protection on all devices, documented incident response processes, a regular compliance review process, provides application access and manages identities for more than 10,000 customers and vendors. The company operates under ISO/IEC 27001/27002 compliance regimes and uses an internally developed solution to monitor and treat its networks, security devices and data. 

Citigroup has recently begun expanding Citigroup IT Operations & Solutions (CITOS) which is a wholly owned subsidiary of Citigroup based in India. With new centers in Mumbai and Chennai, the global IT center will primarily manage and support Citigroup's IT infrastructure including system administration, database administration, information security, network monitoring, and application development for various Citigroup businesses across the world. It is not clear at this time how many of Citigroup's IT needs will ultimately be handled offshore. 

Due to confidentiality issues, Citibank does not outsource much of its IT work.

The company is evaluating cloud solutions for possible implementation and currently runs non-critical application, business application, and storage/backup in the cloud. The company is currently implementing a bring your own device (BYOD) program and uses a mobile device management solution for these devices. 

As of Q2 2013, the company is on a server virtualization initiative with VMware that is set to run through 2013. While a BYOD program is completely in place for Apple devices the company is considering an expansion of this, including the implementation of a virtual desktop infrastructure (VDI), depending on user demand. There is a chance the company will adopt Windows 8 for the company tablets. Blackberry is trending downwards though the company does still support Blackberry Enterprise Server (BES). The company is also considering expanding its SaaS applications.

The IT budget is typically finalized in Q4.





